00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.642
So, today we're going to
continue with our series of

00:00:05.642 --> 00:00:12.502
lectures to come to a conclusion
from the section on population

00:00:12.502 --> 00:00:14.936
and community ecology.

00:00:14.936 --> 00:00:18.808
At last time,
or three lectures ago,

00:00:18.808 --> 00:00:26.000
we were talking about the
regulation of population growth.

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:31.217
And this time,
we're going to move into,

00:00:31.217 --> 00:00:37.638
just wanted to make sure the
boards are in order,

00:00:37.638 --> 00:00:40.046
community ecology.

00:00:40.046 --> 00:00:47.806
And as I said of the first
lecture, this is one of the most

00:00:47.806 --> 00:00:55.030
difficult branches of the
ecological sciences to really

00:00:55.030 --> 00:01:02.254
describe because an ecological
community is a bit of an

00:01:02.254 --> 00:01:06.000
abstract concept.

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:18.937
And one definition is that it's
a collection of species that are

00:01:18.937 --> 00:01:39.000
linked together by their feeding
relationships.
00:01:29&lt;clear/&gt;
 

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:44.125
OK, so it's sort of like the
ecosystem without the

00:01:44.125 --> 00:01:46.949
biogeochemistry in a sense.

00:01:46.949 --> 00:01:53.435
So really what we're looking at
here is the interaction between

00:01:53.435 --> 00:01:59.815
species in a localized area with
respect to how they influence

00:01:59.815 --> 00:02:04.000
each other's fitness,
in a sense.

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:08.642
And these interrelationships
between these species govern all

00:02:08.642 --> 00:02:13.053
of the things that we talked
about in the first half of my

00:02:13.053 --> 00:02:14.059
lectures set.

00:02:14.059 --> 00:02:18.392
It's these interactions that
shape the biogeochemistry of

00:02:18.392 --> 00:02:19.476
those systems.

00:02:19.476 --> 00:02:23.035
So, this is the structure of
the system and the

00:02:23.035 --> 00:02:26.517
biogeochemistry is the function
of the system.

00:02:26.517 --> 00:02:30.000
And it's also these
interactions.

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:39.827
So, they affect the flow of
energy, which we talked about.

00:02:39.827 --> 00:02:45.862
They affect the cycling of
elements.

00:02:45.862 --> 00:02:55.344
They affect the evolution,
the very evolution of species

00:02:55.344 --> 00:03:00.000
within the community.

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:03.466
And these communities self
assemble.

00:03:03.466 --> 00:03:08.022
In other words,
if you start with an empty plot

00:03:08.022 --> 00:03:11.389
of bare land,
we talked about this.

00:03:11.389 --> 00:03:17.035
Remember the example of the
glacier retreating and showing

00:03:17.035 --> 00:03:21.987
the succession of species as the
glacier retreated?

00:03:21.987 --> 00:03:27.830
We started with a bare rock,
and you'll start getting lichen

00:03:27.830 --> 00:03:31.000
growing on the rock.

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:34.785
And then that lichen will
create a little bit of soil,

00:03:34.785 --> 00:03:38.714
allowing plants to come in,
and that the plants increase

00:03:38.714 --> 00:03:39.642
productivity.

00:03:39.642 --> 00:03:43.714
Some of them bring nitrogen
and, allowing shrubs and trees

00:03:43.714 --> 00:03:44.785
and everything.

00:03:44.785 --> 00:03:48.000
And that's the self-assembly of
the community.

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:51.785
Once you have plant there,
you can have insects there.

00:03:51.785 --> 00:03:55.285
Once you have insects there,
you have birds there.

00:03:55.285 --> 00:03:56.571
It self assembles.

00:03:56.571 --> 00:03:59.928
And one of the questions that
ecologists ask is,

00:03:59.928 --> 00:04:03.000
how deterministic is that?

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:08.052
I mean, we know there are some
random components to it,

00:04:08.052 --> 00:04:13.853
and we know that there are some
things that will happen because

00:04:13.853 --> 00:04:17.690
we see it happen over,
and over, and over.

00:04:17.690 --> 00:04:21.339
So the big question is what
must happen?

00:04:21.339 --> 00:04:23.023
What could happen?

00:04:23.023 --> 00:04:25.923
And what might not ever happen?

00:04:25.923 --> 00:04:30.976
That's really one of the
challenges of ecologists is to

00:04:30.976 --> 00:04:37.578
understand those assembly rules
of community if there are any.

00:04:37.578 --> 00:04:41.359
Now, we're not going to really
get into that.

00:04:41.359 --> 00:04:46.343
We are just going to start
looking at the real fundamentals

00:04:46.343 --> 00:04:51.757
of community [SOUND OFF/THEN ON]
which is, what are the possible

00:04:51.757 --> 00:04:55.968
interactions between species
that shape evolution?

00:04:55.968 --> 00:05:07.000
OK.
