00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:13.257
Species interactions:
so, when we talk about species

00:05:13.257 --> 00:05:19.024
interactions and how they
structure communities,

00:05:19.024 --> 00:05:23.196
we have to first define some
terms.

00:05:23.196 --> 00:05:36.000
One is Darwinian fitness.
00:05:27&lt;clear/&gt;
 

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:48.669
And the fitness of an
individual is the relative

00:05:48.669 --> 00:06:03.226
ability of an individual in a
population to survive and

00:06:03.226 --> 00:06:16.000
reproduce.
00:06:07&lt;clear/&gt;
 

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:20.274
So, it's all relative,
OK, within a population.

00:06:20.274 --> 00:06:25.199
And we're going to define also,
we'll be talking about

00:06:25.199 --> 00:06:29.380
adaptations, and I know you know
what this is,

00:06:29.380 --> 00:06:34.769
but let's just make sure that
we are all operating with the

00:06:34.769 --> 00:06:37.000
same assumption.

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:48.576
And an adaptation,
which is something that affects

00:06:48.576 --> 00:07:02.516
the fitness, is a heritable
trait that increases the fitness

00:07:02.516 --> 00:07:15.983
of an individual with respect to
other individuals in that

00:07:15.983 --> 00:07:20.000
population.

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:24.094
So, these are just some
operating assumptions so that

00:07:24.094 --> 00:07:27.165
when we talk about species
interactions,

00:07:27.165 --> 00:07:30.000
there are several
possibilities.

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:34.948
If we have organism one and
organism two,

00:07:34.948 --> 00:07:39.278
we can have,
and we ask how does the

00:07:39.278 --> 00:07:47.072
presence of organism two and the
presence of organism one affect

00:07:47.072 --> 00:07:51.030
the fitness of the two
organisms?

00:07:51.030 --> 00:07:58.082
And if the fitness of both
organisms is increased by being

00:07:58.082 --> 00:08:06.000
in the presence of the other,
that's called mutualism.

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:13.647
Being together increases the
fitness of both relative to when

00:08:13.647 --> 00:08:15.431
they're alone.

00:08:15.431 --> 00:08:21.421
If being together decreases the
fitness of both,

00:08:21.421 --> 00:08:24.735
that's called competition.

00:08:24.735 --> 00:08:32.000
And if you have the situation,
what we recall that?

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:38.054
It could be parasitism,
yeah, parasitism.

00:08:38.054 --> 00:08:39.567
What else?

00:08:39.567 --> 00:08:45.621
Was the ultimate form of
reduced fitness?

00:08:45.621 --> 00:08:51.978
Predation, yeah,
being dead is the ultimate

00:08:51.978 --> 00:08:54.399
reduced fitness.

00:08:54.399 --> 00:09:00.000
So, parasitism and predation.

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:05.018
And then there are some other
sort of rather vague

00:09:05.018 --> 00:09:10.753
interactions where when you put
two individuals together,

00:09:10.753 --> 00:09:16.283
the fitness of one is not
influenced but the fitness of

00:09:16.283 --> 00:09:21.915
the other is either influenced
positively or negatively,

00:09:21.915 --> 00:09:25.909
and we're not going to talk
about those.

00:09:25.909 --> 00:09:29.391
But this one's called
commencalism.

00:09:29.391 --> 00:09:34.000
And this one's called
amensalism.

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:38.219
And obviously there are
gradients.

00:09:38.219 --> 00:09:44.995
Actually, an example of
commencalism is something that

00:09:44.995 --> 00:09:47.424
we've talked about.

00:09:47.424 --> 00:09:54.584
Can anybody think about what
that is when we talked about

00:09:54.584 --> 00:09:55.863
food webs?

00:09:55.863 --> 00:10:02.000
It's kind of a stretch,
but detritivory.

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:06.583
An organism eating detritus,
in a sense, is commencalism

00:10:06.583 --> 00:10:11.500
because it doesn't affect the
fitness of the dead individual

00:10:11.500 --> 00:10:13.666
because it's already dead.

00:10:13.666 --> 00:10:17.416
So, that gets to not having
that much meaning.

00:10:17.416 --> 00:10:21.583
So anyway, these we are not
going to spend time on,

00:10:21.583 --> 00:10:25.500
but they are forms of
interaction that do exist.

00:10:25.500 --> 00:10:28.583
And there are gradients between
these.

00:10:28.583 --> 00:10:33.000
Obviously, it's not all black
and white.

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:44.483
So, we're going to start by
talking about competition.

00:10:44.483 --> 00:10:56.183
And just to remind you,
competition comes in two forms.

00:10:56.183 --> 00:11:07.666
There is intraspecific
competition, which means within

00:11:07.666 --> 00:11:12.000
a species, OK?

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:19.468
And that's not what we're going
to be talking about today,

00:11:19.468 --> 00:11:26.544
but we've already talked about
this without explicitly,

00:11:26.544 --> 00:11:33.559
remember our logistic equation
and the density dependent

00:11:33.559 --> 00:11:38.986
feedback mechanisms in that
population that caused the

00:11:38.986 --> 00:11:44.617
population to deviate from
exponential growth was due to

00:11:44.617 --> 00:11:50.146
intraspecific competition:
individuals within a species

00:11:50.146 --> 00:11:54.139
competing with each other for
resources.

00:11:54.139 --> 00:12:11.000
We are going to talking about
now is more interspecific --
00:12:01&lt;clear/&gt;
 

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:29.000
-- which is competition between
species, OK?

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:33.192
So, I want to show you some
slides that are just from your

00:12:33.192 --> 00:12:37.385
textbook, but just to get you in
the mood for competition.

00:12:37.385 --> 00:12:41.799
So, it comes in all different
forms, and I don't care whether

00:12:41.799 --> 00:12:43.858
you know the names of these.

00:12:43.858 --> 00:12:45.182
It doesn't matter.

00:12:45.182 --> 00:12:49.375
This is just to give you an
idea of the different types of

00:12:49.375 --> 00:12:51.803
competition that we see in
nature.

00:12:51.803 --> 00:12:55.113
This is what's called
consumptive competition,

00:12:55.113 --> 00:12:59.526
and this is just showing the
roots of the trees competing for

00:12:59.526 --> 00:13:01.145
nutrients in the soil.

00:13:01.145 --> 00:13:06.000
Preemptive competition shows
these are barnacles.

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:09.880
We're going to talk a little
bit more about that later,

00:13:09.880 --> 00:13:12.611
just totally taking over the
substrate.

00:13:12.611 --> 00:13:16.061
So no other organism could
possibly settle there.

00:13:16.061 --> 00:13:20.158
Overgrowth competition in
plants where this plant would be

00:13:20.158 --> 00:13:24.542
shading, so other plants that
require a lot of light could not

00:13:24.542 --> 00:13:25.691
grow underneath.

00:13:25.691 --> 00:13:29.429
Chemical competition also
occurs where one plant will

00:13:29.429 --> 00:13:33.094
actually excrete certain
chemicals that create these

00:13:33.094 --> 00:13:37.334
corridors of no growth around
them so other plants can't get

00:13:37.334 --> 00:13:41.000
near to compete for the
nutrients.

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:44.120
The classic form of
competition, say,

00:13:44.120 --> 00:13:48.973
in birds and a lot of higher
organisms is competition for

00:13:48.973 --> 00:13:49.840
territory.

00:13:49.840 --> 00:13:55.126
So these are displays so that
an individual can keep a certain

00:13:55.126 --> 00:14:00.240
territory, and therefore make
that food available to itself,

00:14:00.240 --> 00:14:04.746
therefore increasing its
fitness because it's able to

00:14:04.746 --> 00:14:07.000
feed its young.

00:14:07.000 --> 00:14:12.918
And then this is sort of the
classic, really tooth and claw

00:14:12.918 --> 00:14:18.428
competition where encounter
competition where all these

00:14:18.428 --> 00:14:23.020
species are competing over this
zebra carcass,

00:14:23.020 --> 00:14:25.061
hyena, vultures,
etc.

00:14:25.061 --> 00:14:30.673
OK, now before we can talk more
and more in detail about

00:14:30.673 --> 00:14:37.000
competition, we need to define
the ecological niche.

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:41.656
And this is an interesting
concept in ecology that has been

00:14:41.656 --> 00:14:45.912
around for quite some time,
and it kind of went out of

00:14:45.912 --> 00:14:47.759
popularity for a while.

00:14:47.759 --> 00:14:52.335
And I was gratified to see that
it's made it back into the

00:14:52.335 --> 00:14:56.912
introductory biology textbooks
because I think it's a very

00:14:56.912 --> 00:14:59.000
profound concept.

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:03.949
In this particular competition,
the fundamental ecological

00:15:03.949 --> 00:15:05.598
niche comes from G.

00:15:05.598 --> 00:15:09.679
Evelyn Hutchinson,
who is one of the founders of

00:15:09.679 --> 00:15:10.982
modern ecology.

00:15:10.982 --> 00:15:15.757
He defined as the fundamental
niche of an organism as an

00:15:15.757 --> 00:15:20.619
N-dimensional hypervolume,
every point on which a species

00:15:20.619 --> 00:15:25.395
can survive and reproduce
indefinitely in the absence of

00:15:25.395 --> 00:15:28.000
other species,
OK?

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:32.361
So, this is an abstract
concept, because those species

00:15:32.361 --> 00:15:35.817
are rarely in the absence of
other species,

00:15:35.817 --> 00:15:38.122
except maybe in a test tube.

00:15:38.122 --> 00:15:41.990
But it defines the,
and also we can't even think

00:15:41.990 --> 00:15:44.047
about N-dimensions,
right?

00:15:44.047 --> 00:15:47.915
We're able to think about,
we can envision three

00:15:47.915 --> 00:15:48.820
dimensions.

00:15:48.820 --> 00:15:53.593
But what he's talking about
here, is every single dimension

00:15:53.593 --> 00:15:58.448
in the environment that would
have any effect on the fitness

00:15:58.448 --> 00:16:01.000
of an organism.

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:03.893
So here, just to wrap our
brains around this,

00:16:03.893 --> 00:16:06.063
we're looking at three
dimensions.

00:16:06.063 --> 00:16:09.614
Our organisms here is a
ladybug, and this would be food

00:16:09.614 --> 00:16:09.943
size.

00:16:09.943 --> 00:16:12.507
These guys eat little aphids
and things.

00:16:12.507 --> 00:16:16.190
I don't know if you've ever
used them under house plants,

00:16:16.190 --> 00:16:20.004
but it's a good way to keep
aphids off your house plants if

00:16:20.004 --> 00:16:23.160
you want to introduce ladybugs
to your dorm room,

00:16:23.160 --> 00:16:24.607
which maybe you don't.

00:16:24.607 --> 00:16:27.632
But there's a certain range of
size, food size,

00:16:27.632 --> 00:16:30.000
that they can eat.

00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:32.963
And so, that's three
dimensions.

00:16:32.963 --> 00:16:38.317
There are undoubtedly many
other dimensions that we don't

00:16:38.317 --> 00:16:42.428
even know about,
elements that they require,

00:16:42.428 --> 00:16:42.811
etc.

00:16:42.811 --> 00:16:48.452
So, this would be everywhere,
in this space is a space where

00:16:48.452 --> 00:16:53.614
this organism could survive and
reproduce indefinitely.

00:16:53.614 --> 00:16:59.160
And the reason this concept
lost favor is its something you

00:16:59.160 --> 00:17:04.322
could never ever measure this
because we can't know the

00:17:04.322 --> 00:17:07.000
N-dimensions.

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:10.163
Well, you can never say you
can't know anything,

00:17:10.163 --> 00:17:13.663
but it's very difficult to say
you could know all the

00:17:13.663 --> 00:17:17.163
dimensions that influence the
fitness of an organism.

00:17:17.163 --> 00:17:21.269
But it's still a very important
concept for thinking about it.

00:17:21.269 --> 00:17:24.028
And the niche is not a physical
place, OK?

00:17:24.028 --> 00:17:28.000
The niche of an organism is not
a physical place.

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:30.555
In an N-dimensional
hypervolume.

00:17:30.555 --> 00:17:32.617
It's an abstract concept.

00:17:32.617 --> 00:17:36.821
So this is the fundamental
niche, and here's another

00:17:36.821 --> 00:17:41.851
closely related species whose
niche has some overlap with this

00:17:41.851 --> 00:17:45.561
one, but has different ranges
for temperature,

00:17:45.561 --> 00:17:47.539
humidity, and food size.

00:17:47.539 --> 00:17:52.156
And when you have overlapping
niches is when you have the

00:17:52.156 --> 00:17:55.702
possibility, the potential,
for competition.

00:17:55.702 --> 00:17:59.000
And two things can happen.

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:03.026
If they overlap a lot,
than those two species cannot

00:18:03.026 --> 00:18:05.552
coexist in the same environment.

00:18:05.552 --> 00:18:10.052
One will outcompete the other,
and it will move on to some

00:18:10.052 --> 00:18:14.236
other place where it doesn't
have a strong competitor.

00:18:14.236 --> 00:18:18.184
But if they overlap a little,
you can actually have

00:18:18.184 --> 00:18:20.078
competitive coexistence.

00:18:20.078 --> 00:18:24.815
And we're going to talk about
the results of these degrees of

00:18:24.815 --> 00:18:29.000
niche overlap as we go on in the
lecture.

00:18:29.000 --> 00:18:33.607
So, if the species can makes it
realized, so this is its

00:18:33.607 --> 00:18:37.544
fundamental niche,
this one's fundamental niche,

00:18:37.544 --> 00:18:42.738
and what happens if it can make
its realized niche small enough

00:18:42.738 --> 00:18:46.926
so that there's no niche
overlap, then you can have

00:18:46.926 --> 00:18:51.366
coexistence of those two
species, or very little niche

00:18:51.366 --> 00:18:54.047
overlap in the same environment.

00:18:54.047 --> 00:18:58.654
So that's the difference
between the fundamental and the

00:18:58.654 --> 00:19:01.000
realized niche.

00:19:01.000 --> 00:19:04.765
I think this is from your
textbook.

00:19:04.765 --> 00:19:09.526
This is just one dimension,
seed sized, for,

00:19:09.526 --> 00:19:14.288
say, a bird eating seeds of
this size range.

00:19:14.288 --> 00:19:18.939
We'll be talking about birds a
lot in this.

00:19:18.939 --> 00:19:24.919
And here's partial niche
overlap, species to where they

00:19:24.919 --> 00:19:31.563
eat some seeds of the same size,
but by and large the mode is

00:19:31.563 --> 00:19:34.000
different.

00:19:34.000 --> 00:19:37.129
You can have species
coexisting.

00:19:37.129 --> 00:19:42.883
Partial niche overlap can lead
to competitive coexistence.

00:19:42.883 --> 00:19:48.738
And here's the complete overlap
in just this one dimension,

00:19:48.738 --> 00:19:52.876
which would lead to competitive
exclusion.

00:19:52.876 --> 00:19:59.236
But obviously it matters what's
happening on all the dimensions.

00:19:59.236 --> 00:20:02.668
This is just an
oversimplification,

00:20:02.668 --> 00:20:06.000
to give you the idea.

