competition experiments that's

00:21:24.578 --> 00:21:29.000
carried out by Gause way back in
1934 --

00:21:29.000 --> 00:21:34.872
-- that I'm just going to use
to illustrate the concept of

00:21:34.872 --> 00:21:40.024
competitive exclusion,
because these were done with

00:21:40.024 --> 00:21:44.763
very simple protozoa in a test
tube, paramecia,

00:21:44.763 --> 00:21:50.121
and actually this was back in
the days when they were

00:21:50.121 --> 00:21:54.963
developing these theories for
population growth.

00:21:54.963 --> 00:21:59.909
And these organisms were
growing according to the

00:21:59.909 --> 00:22:03.000
logistic equation.

00:22:03.000 --> 00:22:06.565
So here we are with,
and this is the classic

00:22:06.565 --> 00:22:11.458
experiment actually in your
textbook that they talk about in

00:22:11.458 --> 00:22:14.360
the context of the ecological
niche.

00:22:14.360 --> 00:22:16.848
So this is Paramecia caudatum.

00:22:16.848 --> 00:22:19.253
These names aren't important.

00:22:19.253 --> 00:22:22.985
Don't worry about it,
but we have to call them

00:22:22.985 --> 00:22:23.814
something.

00:22:23.814 --> 00:22:25.224
P.
aurelia, which,

00:22:25.224 --> 00:22:30.282
when grown alone in a test tube
grow according to the logistic

00:22:30.282 --> 00:22:35.092
equation, they grow up and then
they level off at a certain

00:22:35.092 --> 00:22:37.000
level.

00:22:37.000 --> 00:22:43.559
And what Gause did is that he
wanted to see,

00:22:43.559 --> 00:22:51.796
look at this phenomenon of
competition and he grew them

00:22:51.796 --> 00:23:00.338
together, and he found that,
actually that no matter what

00:23:00.338 --> 00:23:08.423
combination he put in,
aurelia would always win out in

00:23:08.423 --> 00:23:21.000
competitive exclusion.
00:23:13&lt;clear/&gt;
 

00:23:21.000 --> 00:23:24.577
And he learned through a series
of experiments,

00:23:24.577 --> 00:23:28.933
we don't have time to go into
the details, but this would

00:23:28.933 --> 00:23:33.599
always occur if you made two
species compete in a very simple

00:23:33.599 --> 00:23:35.000
environment.

00:23:35.000 --> 00:23:39.462
In the test tube where he was
feeding these guys exactly the

00:23:39.462 --> 00:23:43.394
same food, some form of
bacteria, in a test tube this

00:23:43.394 --> 00:23:47.630
one would always outcompete the
other, and there would be

00:23:47.630 --> 00:23:49.294
competitive exclusion.

00:23:49.294 --> 00:23:54.058
If he made the environment more
complex, where there were layers

00:23:54.058 --> 00:23:58.521
in it, or there was sediment in
the bottom of the test tube,

00:23:58.521 --> 00:24:02.000
that allowed more niche
dimensions.

00:24:02.000 --> 00:24:06.000
There were conditions under
which the competitive

00:24:06.000 --> 00:24:08.416
coexistence would be allowed.

00:24:08.416 --> 00:24:13.333
And he actually developed a set
of equations to describe his

00:24:13.333 --> 00:24:16.916
competition that I'm going to
write for you.

00:24:16.916 --> 00:24:21.833
We're not going to use them;
we're not going to analyze them

00:24:21.833 --> 00:24:26.833
in detail, but I'm just going to
show them to you so that you

00:24:26.833 --> 00:24:31.250
have an appreciation for how
population ecologists and

00:24:31.250 --> 00:24:37.000
community ecologists start to
think about these systems.

00:24:37.000 --> 00:24:44.172
So, he said we can model this
interaction using our logistic

00:24:44.172 --> 00:24:45.266
equation.

00:24:45.266 --> 00:24:50.615
So he said dN/dt would be the
growth rate of,

00:24:50.615 --> 00:24:54.019
let's call, the top one,
one.

00:24:54.019 --> 00:24:58.517
It doesn't matter what you call
which.

00:24:58.517 --> 00:25:01.313
The dN/dt equals r1,
N1.

00:25:01.313 --> 00:25:08.000
Now here's our logistic,
K1 minus N1 over K.

00:25:08.000 --> 00:25:15.032
But he said I'm going to modify
this equation so that the actual

00:25:15.032 --> 00:25:21.060
growth of the organism is
reduced to some amount that's

00:25:21.060 --> 00:25:27.423
proportional to the number of
the other organisms that are

00:25:27.423 --> 00:25:28.093
there.

00:25:28.093 --> 00:25:32.000
So, he called that alpha-N2.

00:25:32.000 --> 00:25:40.673
OK, so some amount that's
proportional to amount the other

00:25:40.673 --> 00:25:43.717
species that's here.

00:25:43.717 --> 00:25:50.260
And then, he said dN2/DT is
equal to r2, N2,

00:25:50.260 --> 00:25:57.717
K2 minus N2 minus beta-N1 over,
this should be K1,

00:25:57.717 --> 00:26:00.000
over K2.

00:26:00.000 --> 00:26:05.251
So, the growth rate of species
to in the presence of species

00:26:05.251 --> 00:26:10.146
one is reduced by some amount
that's proportional to the

00:26:10.146 --> 00:26:12.371
abundance of species one.

00:26:12.371 --> 00:26:17.623
And these, the values of these,
these are called competition

00:26:17.623 --> 00:26:18.780
coefficients.

00:26:18.780 --> 00:26:23.675
You can actually do experiments
and put values on these,

00:26:23.675 --> 00:26:28.659
and they are a measure of how
strong a competitor each of

00:26:28.659 --> 00:26:34.000
these species are with respect
to the other one.

00:26:34.000 --> 00:26:37.854
So, you're not going to have to
deal with these,

00:26:37.854 --> 00:26:42.447
but I just wanted you to see
them, and see how population

00:26:42.447 --> 00:26:45.646
ecologists began to model these
systems.

00:26:45.646 --> 00:26:50.239
And so, it's the relative
values of these relative to the

00:26:50.239 --> 00:26:54.914
carrying capacities that will
ultimately determine whether

00:26:54.914 --> 00:27:00.000
species will coexist or not when
they are competing.

00:27:00.000 --> 00:27:03.457
OK, so that's more of a
theoretical analysis.

00:27:03.457 --> 00:27:05.972
Now let's look at the real
world.

00:27:05.972 --> 00:27:09.981
Competitive exclusion,
that is, the exclusion of one

00:27:09.981 --> 00:27:14.617
species from an environment
because of strong competition in

00:27:14.617 --> 00:27:18.940
another, is very difficult to
study, because if it's not

00:27:18.940 --> 00:27:22.398
there, you don't know it was
excluded, right?

00:27:22.398 --> 00:27:26.878
I mean, you don't go to some
place and say I don't see the

00:27:26.878 --> 00:27:29.000
species here.

00:27:29.000 --> 00:27:33.694
It must have been eliminated by
competitive exclusion.

00:27:33.694 --> 00:27:36.440
It might never have been there.

00:27:36.440 --> 00:27:41.665
So, the way we learn about this
phenomenon is either through

00:27:41.665 --> 00:27:46.537
inadvertent experiments,
and that is the introduction of

00:27:46.537 --> 00:27:51.231
species to new environments and
then see what happens,

00:27:51.231 --> 00:27:55.128
or actual intentional
ecological experiments.

00:27:55.128 --> 00:28:00.000
So, we're going to talk about
both of those.

00:28:00.000 --> 00:28:11.000
And the first one --
00:28:01&lt;clear/&gt;
 

00:28:11.000 --> 00:28:26.000
-- we'll talk about invasions --
00:28:12&lt;clear/&gt;
 

00:28:26.000 --> 00:28:30.022
-- and competitive exclusion.

00:28:30.022 --> 00:28:38.206
And one of the classic examples
of this is the zebra mussel.

00:28:38.206 --> 00:28:41.951
I don't know what happened.

00:28:41.951 --> 00:28:44.170
Oh, there it is.

00:28:44.170 --> 00:28:48.887
I didn't realize this was
animated.

00:28:48.887 --> 00:28:53.603
That's why there was nothing
there.

00:28:53.603 --> 00:29:01.787
So, the zebra mussel is a tiny
mussel that was introduced to

00:29:01.787 --> 00:29:09.000
the United States back in,
I guess, 1988.

00:29:09.000 --> 00:29:11.857
And up here,
introduced into the Great Lakes

00:29:11.857 --> 00:29:16.044
by ships just being attached to
ships, or it's possible it might

00:29:16.044 --> 00:29:18.636
have been the larvae in ships'
ballasts.

00:29:18.636 --> 00:29:21.825
Ships go into port,
they take on water into their

00:29:21.825 --> 00:29:25.082
ballasts to stabilize,
and then they go to another

00:29:25.082 --> 00:29:26.411
port and let it out.

00:29:26.411 --> 00:29:30.000
And they're filled with larvae
and species.

00:29:30.000 --> 00:29:37.785
So, the entire world oceans are
now filled with introduced

00:29:37.785 --> 00:29:41.609
species from ships ballasts.

00:29:41.609 --> 00:29:43.658
So here's 1988.

00:29:43.658 --> 00:29:48.712
The zebra mussel is there.
1990: here.

00:29:48.712 --> 00:29:52.126
92: here.
94, 90 whatever,

00:29:52.126 --> 00:29:53.356
oh, 2001.

00:29:53.356 --> 00:29:58.000
It spread amazingly fast.

00:29:58.000 --> 00:30:03.631
And it is this tiny little
mussel that seems to thrive

00:30:03.631 --> 00:30:07.562
everywhere: clogs,
all kinds of pipes,

00:30:07.562 --> 00:30:13.406
settles on top of other native
shellfish and kills them,

00:30:13.406 --> 00:30:19.250
and has led to extensive
competitive exclusion of native

00:30:19.250 --> 00:30:22.968
shellfish in a number of
ecosystems.

00:30:22.968 --> 00:30:29.343
Some of the effects of these:
in some ecosystems they cleared

00:30:29.343 --> 00:30:32.000
up the water.

00:30:32.000 --> 00:30:36.701
They are able to filter just an
amazing amount of water when

00:30:36.701 --> 00:30:37.976
they're feeding.

00:30:37.976 --> 00:30:42.997
So they actually have increased
the clarity of the water in many

00:30:42.997 --> 00:30:47.539
ecosystems, filtering out
plankton, which allows the light

00:30:47.539 --> 00:30:52.321
to penetrate deeper in those
systems, allowing aquatic plants

00:30:52.321 --> 00:30:54.233
to grow from the bottom.

00:30:54.233 --> 00:30:59.015
So the introduction of this one
species can completely change

00:30:59.015 --> 00:31:03.000
the structure of the entire
ecosystem.

00:31:03.000 --> 00:31:04.491
I just heard a lecture.

00:31:04.491 --> 00:31:07.992
I was just visiting the
Institute for Ecosystem Studies

00:31:07.992 --> 00:31:09.872
which is out in Millbrook,
NY.

00:31:09.872 --> 00:31:13.698
By the way, if any of you are
looking for summer internships

00:31:13.698 --> 00:31:17.394
and are interested in ecology,
they have a fabulous summer

00:31:17.394 --> 00:31:18.625
internship program.

00:31:18.625 --> 00:31:22.062
I've had several students go
there that have had great

00:31:22.062 --> 00:31:22.840
experiences.

00:31:22.840 --> 00:31:26.147
But there's somebody there
studying the zebra mussel

00:31:26.147 --> 00:31:29.000
invasion in the Hudson River.

00:31:29.000 --> 00:31:33.191
And he showed this incredibly
depressing graph of over the

00:31:33.191 --> 00:31:37.602
last ten years of the native
mussels in that river going down

00:31:37.602 --> 00:31:39.367
to basically extinction.

00:31:39.367 --> 00:31:43.044
And then, this is the weird
thing about ecosystems,

00:31:43.044 --> 00:31:45.985
just last year it started to
turn around.

00:31:45.985 --> 00:31:50.470
And they haven't done anything
to eradicate the zebra mussels,

00:31:50.470 --> 00:31:54.441
but the native mussels are
starting to have a comeback.

00:31:54.441 --> 00:31:58.264
And nobody knows why,
and nobody knows whether it's a

00:31:58.264 --> 00:32:04.000
real comeback because it could
come back for a couple of years.

00:32:04.000 --> 00:32:09.742
So, it's really interesting how
unpredictable these complex

00:32:09.742 --> 00:32:10.930
systems are.

00:32:10.930 --> 00:32:16.772
But these mussels can cause
millions and millions of dollars

00:32:16.772 --> 00:32:17.762
of damage.

00:32:17.762 --> 00:32:23.702
And I also learned on that trip
that ecologists are trying to

00:32:23.702 --> 00:32:29.742
get in place policies that if an
industry for whatever reasons

00:32:29.742 --> 00:32:34.000
wants to intentionally
introduce,

00:32:34.000 --> 00:32:37.786
Here's an example of an
application of fundamental

00:32:37.786 --> 00:32:39.409
ecological knowledge.

00:32:39.409 --> 00:32:43.659
The reason people study the
ecology of invasive species,

00:32:43.659 --> 00:32:47.754
understanding this competitive
exclusion and all that,

00:32:47.754 --> 00:32:52.004
is that you want to use that
understanding to be able to

00:32:52.004 --> 00:32:56.331
predict, if you introduce a new
species to a new habitat,

00:32:56.331 --> 00:33:01.045
whether it will be invasive or
not, there are some species you

00:33:01.045 --> 00:33:05.759
can introduce and they will fit
right in and not exclude every

00:33:05.759 --> 00:33:08.000
other species.

00:33:08.000 --> 00:33:12.672
And so, what they're trying to
put in place is insurance that a

00:33:12.672 --> 00:33:16.742
company would have to buy that
was either intentionally

00:33:16.742 --> 00:33:20.660
introducing a species,
or whatever practice that they

00:33:20.660 --> 00:33:23.976
were doing was likely to
introduce a species,

00:33:23.976 --> 00:33:28.197
and the cost of that insurance
would be a function of the

00:33:28.197 --> 00:33:32.342
probability of that species
actually causing competitive

00:33:32.342 --> 00:33:34.000
exclusion.

00:33:34.000 --> 00:33:38.981
And this is something that
people are trying to put into

00:33:38.981 --> 00:33:42.695
place in to the economic system
basically.

00:33:42.695 --> 00:33:47.586
So, it puts a new meaning to
limited liability company,

00:33:47.586 --> 00:33:47.949
LLC.

00:33:47.949 --> 00:33:53.112
So, you have to insure your
liability, which I think would

00:33:53.112 --> 00:33:59.000
go a long way to reduce some of
these ecological crises.

00:33:59.000 --> 00:34:02.035
OK, so that's an inadvertent
experiment.

00:34:02.035 --> 00:34:05.227
Now there are many,
many examples of this.

00:34:05.227 --> 00:34:08.419
There's books written on
invasive species.

00:34:08.419 --> 00:34:13.089
And if I can get this thing to
work, I'll show you some clips

00:34:13.089 --> 00:34:15.191
of invasive species,
snakes.

00:34:15.191 --> 00:34:19.550
And the biggest impact is on
islands because islands have

00:34:19.550 --> 00:34:24.143
been isolated ecosystems for so
long that if you introduce a

00:34:24.143 --> 00:34:26.790
species, you have dramatic
changes.

00:34:26.790 --> 00:34:29.904
In Australia,
a big example was a prickly

00:34:29.904 --> 00:34:34.808
pear cactus which was introduced
many years ago to create living

00:34:34.808 --> 00:34:38.000
fences for livestock.

00:34:38.000 --> 00:34:42.693
They completely took over not
all of the grasslands,

00:34:42.693 --> 00:34:47.754
but a lot of the grasslands and
turn them into thickets.

00:34:47.754 --> 00:34:52.263
OK, so invasive species are
inadvertent ecological

00:34:52.263 --> 00:34:53.368
experiments.

00:34:53.368 --> 00:34:57.049
Let's talk about intentional
experiments.

00:34:57.049 --> 00:35:02.662
And this is also very classic
textbook experiment that was one

00:35:02.662 --> 00:35:08.000
of the first ecological
experiments to be done.

00:35:08.000 --> 00:35:10.487
And it was done with barnacles.

00:35:10.487 --> 00:35:15.220
This was Joseph Connell was a
professor at the University of

00:35:15.220 --> 00:35:17.306
California, Santa Barbara.

00:35:17.306 --> 00:35:21.638
Barnacles have a larval stage
that floats around in the

00:35:21.638 --> 00:35:24.767
plankton, and then they settle
on rocks.

00:35:24.767 --> 00:35:28.939
So this was a classic barnacle
ecosystem in Scotland,

00:35:28.939 --> 00:35:33.593
actually, in which the upper
inner tidal there is a species

00:35:33.593 --> 00:35:36.000
called Chthamalus.

00:35:36.000 --> 00:35:39.816
And then the lower was
dominated by a species of mussel

00:35:39.816 --> 00:35:40.876
called Balanus.

00:35:40.876 --> 00:35:44.835
So, he asked the question,
is this distribution where the

00:35:44.835 --> 00:35:48.015
two are exclusive of one
another, is it due to

00:35:48.015 --> 00:35:51.691
competition between them,
or is it just that this one

00:35:51.691 --> 00:35:54.659
tolerates desiccation longer
than this one?

00:35:54.659 --> 00:35:57.981
The inner tidal zone,
the tide goes up and down,

00:35:57.981 --> 00:36:03.000
so this one's going to be
exposed to dryness a lot longer.

00:36:03.000 --> 00:36:05.596
So, how do you answer that
question?

00:36:05.596 --> 00:36:10.195
Well, you do an experiment and
so what he did was he took rocks

00:36:10.195 --> 00:36:13.087
from the upper,
inner tidal that had the

00:36:13.087 --> 00:36:16.722
Chthamalus on them,
and he moved them to the lower

00:36:16.722 --> 00:36:17.019
one.

00:36:17.019 --> 00:36:21.024
And he let the Balanus,
the species that dominates down

00:36:21.024 --> 00:36:23.175
here colonize on those rocks.

00:36:23.175 --> 00:36:27.329
But then he divided them in
half, and removed the Balanus

00:36:27.329 --> 00:36:30.000
from half of the rock.

00:36:30.000 --> 00:36:34.451
And then he monitored the
survivorship of the Chthamalus.

00:36:34.451 --> 00:36:39.300
And remember the survivorship
curves that we talked about when

00:36:39.300 --> 00:36:43.194
we created those life tables,
he actually measured

00:36:43.194 --> 00:36:45.500
survivorship curves on these.

00:36:45.500 --> 00:36:49.951
If you go to the original
paper, you see LX is a function

00:36:49.951 --> 00:36:50.587
of time.

00:36:50.587 --> 00:36:54.482
So that's a tool that we use,
to ask the question,

00:36:54.482 --> 00:36:58.376
is the survivorship of
Chthamalus increased in the

00:36:58.376 --> 00:37:01.000
absence of Balanus?

00:37:01.000 --> 00:37:04.800
And this is all from your
textbook, showing that the

00:37:04.800 --> 00:37:08.675
percent of mortality,
when a competitor is present is

00:37:08.675 --> 00:37:11.730
much higher than the competitor
is absent.

00:37:11.730 --> 00:37:15.903
So, he's able to show directly
that there was competition

00:37:15.903 --> 00:37:17.096
between the two.

00:37:17.096 --> 00:37:19.555
And in fact,
this was that kind of

00:37:19.555 --> 00:37:24.100
aggressive kind of competition
where one just plucks the other

00:37:24.100 --> 00:37:25.367
one off the rock.

00:37:25.367 --> 00:37:28.125
I mean it's direct:
you're on my rock;

00:37:28.125 --> 00:37:32.000
get out of here,
and it pops it off.

00:37:32.000 --> 00:37:37.545
He also was able to show that
tolerance to desiccation is also

00:37:37.545 --> 00:37:39.727
a factor in this system.

00:37:39.727 --> 00:37:43.181
It's not like it's totally
competition.

00:37:43.181 --> 00:37:48.363
But competition was playing a
role, and so I've summarized

00:37:48.363 --> 00:37:52.000
that in this slide using our
terminology.

00:37:52.000 --> 00:37:57.454
He was able to show that the
fundamental niche of Chthamalus,

00:37:57.454 --> 00:38:04.148
in other words --
-- the region in the inner

00:38:04.148 --> 00:38:13.723
tidal, where the larvae could
actually settle and live in the

00:38:13.723 --> 00:38:23.776
absence of competitors was much
broader than the realized niche.

00:38:23.776 --> 00:38:30.000
All right, so let's get this
over.

00:38:30.000 --> 00:38:36.039
This is from your textbook.

00:38:36.039 --> 00:38:49.013
And we're going to just use,
I'm going to use an example of

00:38:49.013 --> 00:38:50.131
that.

00:38:50.131 --> 00:39:14.000
So, competition can also lead
to character displacement --
00:39:04&lt;clear/&gt;
 

00:39:14.000 --> 00:39:22.869
-- which in turn can lead to
actual competitive coexistence.

00:39:22.869 --> 00:39:30.084
And an example of this,
we're going to talk about

00:39:30.084 --> 00:39:37.000
Darwin's finches in the
Galapagos Islands.

00:39:37.000 --> 00:39:47.229
And one of the ways that
ecologists actually measure,

00:39:47.229 --> 00:39:55.688
that's a bird,
in case you didn't notice it.

00:39:55.688 --> 00:40:01.000
And this is beak depth.

00:40:01.000 --> 00:40:07.785
The shape and size of a beak
tells you what kinds of seeds a

00:40:07.785 --> 00:40:12.846
bird can eat,
and so they measured beak depth

00:40:12.846 --> 00:40:18.827
as a niche dimension,
basically, because it tells you

00:40:18.827 --> 00:40:22.507
what size seeds the bird can
eat.

00:40:22.507 --> 00:40:28.488
And a study was done;
we're going to make the islands

